INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (142,'199700103005','$$(1-\\frac{x}{3})^9=1+9(-\\frac{x}{3})+36(-\\frac{x}{3})^2+84(-\\frac{x}{3})^3+...$$;=$$1-3x+4x^2-\\frac{28}{9}x^3+...$$;since coefficient of $$x^3$$ is of interest to us, we only need to consider the terms $$4x^2$$ and $$-\\frac{28}{9}x^3$$ in the expansion of $$(1-\\frac{x}{3})^9$$;$$(9+8x)(1-\\frac{x}{3})^9=(9+8x)(1-3x+4x^2-\\frac{28}{9}x^3+...)$$;$$\\Rightarrow  term involving  x^3  in the equation$$;= $$[9(-\\frac{28}{9})+8(4)]x^3=4x^3$$;therefore coefficient of $$x^3$$ = 4 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (143,'199700103006','$$y=\\frac{ ((3x-2)^{10})}{6}$$therefore ;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{10}{6}(3x-2)^9(3)$$;=$$5(3x-2)^9$$;when $$x = \\frac{1}{3}$$ ;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=5(3(\\frac{1}{3})-2)^9$$;= - 5;Rate of change of x,;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d}x }{\\mathrm{d} t}=2s^{-1} at  x=\\frac{1}{3}$$;therefore at $$x=\\frac{1}{3}$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} t}=(-5)(2)=-10s^{-1}$$;Hence rate of change of y at $$x=\\frac{1}{3}$$ is - 10 units per second. (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (144,'199700103007','a) $$f:x \\mapsto  5-\\frac{6}{x} , x\\neq 0$$;Let ;$$y=f(x)$$;$$\\Rightarrow  y=5-\\frac{6}{x}$$;$$\\Rightarrow  \\frac{6}{x}=5-y$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{ 1}{x}=\\frac{1}{6} (5-y)$$;$$\\Rightarrow  x=\\frac{6}{(5-y)},y\\neq 5$$;therefore $$f^{-1}(x)= \\frac{6}{(5-x)},x\\neq 5$$ (ANS);b) To find x such that ;$$f(x)=f^{-1}(x)$$we have ;$$5-\\frac{6}{x}=\\frac{6}{(5-x)}$$;$$\\Rightarrow\\frac{ (5x-6)}{x}=\\frac{6}{(5-x)}$$;$$\\Rightarrow (5x-6)(5-x)=6x$$;$$\\Rightarrow 25x-5x^2-30+6x=6x$$;$$\\Rightarrow 5x^2-25x+30=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow x^2-5x+6=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (x-2)(x-3)=0$$;therefore x = 2 or x = 3 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (145,'199700103008','i)$$\\vec{OA}=3i+j=\\binom{3}{1}$$;$$\\vec{OC}=4-2j=\\binom{4}{-2}$$;by vector addition,;$$\\vec{OB}=\\vec{OC}+\\vec{CB}$$;=$$\\vec{OC}+\\vec{OA}$$;=$$\\binom{4}{-2}+\\binom{3}{1}$$;=$$\\binom{7}{1}$$ (ANS);ii) To find acute angle \\theta between the diagonals of the parallelogram OABC, apply vector scalar dot-product of diagonals OB and AC.;$$\\vec{AC}=\\vec{OC}-\\vec{OA}=\\binom{4}{-2}-\\binom{3}{1}=\\binom{1}{-3}$$;Now;$$|\\vec{OB}|=\\sqrt{7^2+(-1)^2}=\\sqrt{50}=5\\sqrt2$$;$$|\\vec{AC}|=\\sqrt{1^2+(-3)^2}=\\sqrt{10}$$;$$\\vec{OB} \\ast \\vec{AC}=\\binom{7}{-1} \\ast \\binom{1}{-3}=7+(-1)(-3)=10$$;$$\\Rightarrow  \\cos  \\theta  = \\frac{ (\\vec{OB} \\ast \\vec{AC})}{(|\\vec{OB}| \\ast |\\vec{AC}|)}= \\frac{10}{((5\\sqrt2)\\sqrt{10})}=\\sqrt{\\frac{1}{5}}=\\sqrt{0.2}=0.4472$$;therefore ;$$\\theta  = \\cos ^{-1}(0.4472)=63.43^{\\circ}$$;=$$63.4^{\\circ}$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (146,'199700103009','a) The reflex angle AOB = $$2\\pi -\\frac{ (2\\pi )}{5}=2\\pi (\\frac{4}{5})=\\frac{ (8\\pi )}{5}$$	therefore The major arc ACB = $$\\frac{ (8\\pi )}{5}(10)=16\\pi $$;= 50.27 cm (ANS);b) Area of triangle AOB = $$\\frac{1}{2}r^2\\sin  \\alpha $$;=$$\\frac{1}{2}(10)^2\\sin (\\frac{ (2\\pi )}{5})$$;=$$47.55cm^2$$;Area of circular sector AOB ;= $$\\frac{1}{2}r^2\\alpha $$;=$$\\frac{1}{2}(10)^2(\\frac{ (2\\pi )}{5})$$;=$$20\\pi $$;=$$62.83cm^2$$			      therefore area of shaded region = 62.83 - 47.55 = $$15.28 cm^2$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (147,'199700103010','i) To find acceleration, we differentiate v with respect to t,;Acceleration,;$$a=\\frac{\\mathrm{d} v}{\\mathrm{d}t} =5(2t)+(1-3p)$$;= (10t) + (1 - 3p) (ANS);ii) Acceleration, a = 3 when t = 2;$$\\Rightarrow  3=10(2)+(1-3p)$$;$$\\Rightarrow  3p=20+1-3=18$$;ie. p = 6 (ANS);iii) Now $$v=5t^2-17t+6ms^{-1}$$;since p = 6;To find values of t when the particle is at instantaneous rest, we solve for t when v = 0;$$\\Rightarrow 5t^2-17t+6=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (5t-2)(t-3)=0$$;$$t=\\frac{2}{3}s or 3s$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (148,'199700103011','a) i) To find coordinates of A and B, solve the simultaneous equation;$$y=x^2-8x+24$$ ……(1);$$y=8x-x^2$$ ……..(2);Eliminating y from (1) and (2),;$$x^2-8x+24 =8x-x^2$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2x^2-16x+24=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow x^2-8x+12=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (x-6)(x-2)=0$$;when x = 2, y = 12;when x = 6, y = 12;Therefore A(2, 12) and B (6, 12) (ANS);ii)   Area of shaded region;= $$\\int _2^6(y_1-y_2)dx$$;= $$\\int _2^6[(8x-x^2)-(x^2-8x+24)]dx$$;= $$\\int _2^6(16x-2x^2-24)dx$$;= $$[8x^2-\\frac{2}{3}x^3-24x]_2^6$$;= $$[8(36)-\\frac{2}{3}(216)-24(6)]-[32-\\frac{16}{3}-48]$$;= $$144-43\\frac{2}{3}+16+\\frac{16}{3}$$;= $$160-\\frac{416}{3}$$;= $$23 \\frac{1}{3}units^2$$ (ANS);  b) The volume generated ;= $$\\int _{x=1}^4 \\pi y^2dx$$;=$$\\int _1^4\\pi (5+4x-x^2)dx$$;=$$\\pi [5x+2x^2-\\frac{1}{3}x^3]_1^4$$;=$$\\pi [(20+32-\\frac{64}{3})-(7-\\frac{1}{3})]$$;=$$\\pi [45-\\frac{63}{3}]$$;=$$24\\pi $$;= $$75.40 units^3$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (149,'199700103012','i) Gradient of curve,;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=y^1=x^2+1\\frac{6}{x}^2, where  x>0$$;$$P -= (4, 18)$$;Gradient of tangent at P = $$4^2+\\frac{16}{4^2}=16+1=17$$;Therefore gradient of the normal to the curve at P = $$-\\frac{1}{17}$$Equation of the normal at P is given by;$$y-18=-\\frac{1}{17}(x-4)$$;or;$$y+\\frac{1}{17}x-\\frac{18 4}{17}=0$$ (ANS);ii) To find the equation of the curve, integrate the gradient equation,;$$\\Rightarrow y=\\int \\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}dx$$;=$$\\int x^2+1\\frac{6}{x}^2dx$$;=$$\\frac{1}{3}x^3-1\\frac{6}{x}+C$$ where C is the integration constant to be determined.;Now ;$$P -= (4,18)$$;$$18=\\frac{64}{3}-\\frac{16}{4}+C$$;$$C=22-\\frac{64}{3}=\\frac{2}{3}$$;Hence $$y=\\frac{1}{3}x^3-1\\frac{6}{x}+\\frac{2}{3}$$ is the equation of the curve (ANS);Now;$$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d} ^{2}y}{\\mathrm{d} x^{2}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{d} }{\\mathrm{d} x}(\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x})=y^11=2x-\\frac{32}{x^3} ;x>0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2x-\\frac{32}{x^3}=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow x^4=16$$;i.e x = 2;When x = 2,;$$y=\\frac{8}{3}-8+\\frac{2}{3}=-\\frac{14}{3}$$;therefore coordinates of the point  is $$(2,- \\frac{14}{3})$$ (ANS);Minimum value of the gradient = $$2^2+\\frac{16}{2^2}=4+4$$= 8 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (150,'199700103013','i) Surface area of the circular cylinder;= $$\\pi r^2+2\\pi rh$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\pi r^2+2\\pi rh=432\\pi $$;$$\\Rightarrow r^2+2rh=432$$;i.e $$h=\\frac{1}{(2r)(432-r^2)}$$; Volume of cylinder ;= $$\\pi r^2h$$; =$$\\pi r^2[\\frac{1}{(2r)}(432-r^2)]$$;$$V=\\frac{\\pi }{2}(432r-r^3)$$ (SHOWN);ii) To find r for which V is stationary, we solve for r such that;$$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d} V}{\\mathrm{d} r}=0$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} V}{\\mathrm{d} r}= \\frac{\\pi }{2}(432-3r^2)$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} V}{\\mathrm{d} r}=0 \\Rightarrow  432-3r^2=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow r^2=43\\frac{2}{3}=144$$;r = 12 (ANS);iii) Volume of cylinder, V ;=$$ \\frac{\\pi }{2}r(432-r^2)$$;=$$6\\pi (432-144)$$;=$$1728\\pi $$;$$\\approx 5430 cm^3$$ (ANS);since $$\\approx 5430 cm^3$$ > 0, it is a minimum value. (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (151,'199700103014','a) $$16\\sin x-8\\sin ^2x=5\\cos ^2x$$;  $$\\Rightarrow 16\\sin x-8\\sin ^2x = 5-5\\sin ^2x$$;$$\\Rightarrow 3\\sin ^2x-16\\sin x+5=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (3\\sin x-1)(\\sin x-5)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\sin x=\\frac{1}{3} or \\sin x=5$$ (Rejected);therefore $$x=\\sin ^{-1}(\\frac{1}{3}) or x=\\pi -\\sin ^{-1}(\\frac{1}{3})$$;Hence x = $$19.5^{\\circ} or ;x=180^{\\circ}-19.5^{\\circ}=160.5^{\\circ}$$ (ANS);ii) $$4\\sin y\\cos y-3\\cos ^2y=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\cos y(4\\sin y-3\\cos y)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\cos y=0 or 4\\sin y=3\\cos y$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=90^{\\circ},270^{\\circ} or \\tan y=\\frac{3}{4}$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=90^{\\circ},270^{\\circ} or y=\\tan ^{-1}(\\frac{3}{4}),\\pi +\\tan ^{-1}(\\frac{3}{4})$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=90^{\\circ},270^{\\circ} or y=36.87^{\\circ},216.87^{\\circ}$$;Hence y = $$36.87^{\\circ}, 90^{\\circ}, 216.87^{\\circ}, 270^{\\circ}$$ (ANS); iii)$$sec(\\frac{ (3z)}{2}-18^{\\circ})+2=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow secx=-2$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\cos x=\\frac{1}{(secx)}=-\\frac{1}{2}$$;$$\\Rightarrow x=\\cos ^{-1}(\\frac{1}{(-2)}) or \\pi -\\cos ^{-1}(\\frac{1}{(-2)})$$;$$\\Rightarrow x=120^{\\circ} or 240^{\\circ}$$;Substituting x in terms of z to find values of z,;therefore;$$ \\frac{ (3z)}{2}-18^{\\circ}=120^{\\circ} or 240^{\\circ} or 480^{\\circ}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{ (3z)}{2}=138^{\\circ} or 258^{\\circ} or 498^{\\circ}$$;$$\\Rightarrow z=\\frac{2}{3}(138^{\\circ}) or \\frac{2}{3}(258^{\\circ}) or \\frac{2}{3}(498^{\\circ})$$;i.e $$z=92^{\\circ} or 172^{\\circ} or 332^{\\circ}$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (152,'199700103015','a) To find C, we apply;$$\\vec{AB}=\\vec{DC}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\vec{OB}-\\vec{OA}=\\vec{OC}-\\vec{OD}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\vec{OC}=\\vec{OB}-\\vec{OA}+ \\vec{OD}$$;therefore $$\\vec{OC} = \\binom{2}{7}-\\binom{-1}{4}+\\binom{1}{0}))=\\binom{4}{3}$$;Hence, we have C(4, 3) (ANS);To find E, by ratio theorem,;$$\\vec{OE}=\\frac{1}{3}(2\\vec{OB}+\\vec{OC})$$;=$$\\frac{1}{3}[2\\binom{2}{7}+\\binom{4}{3}]$$;=$$\\frac{1}{3}\\binom{8}{17}$$;=$$\\binom{\\frac{8}{3}}{\\frac{17}{3}}$$;Therefore E$$(\\frac{8}{3}, \\frac{17}{3})$$ (ANS);b) Gradient of DC = $$\\frac{ (3-0)}{(4-1)}=1$$therefore equation of line is (y - 0)=1(x - 1) using D(1, 0);i.e y = x - 1........equation of line DC (ANS);therefore x-c\\infty rdinate of F = $$\\frac{8}{3}$$When x = $$\\frac{8}{3}$$,;y = $$\\frac{8}{3} - 1 = \\frac{5}{3}$$;$$y - c\\infty rdinate of F$$;hence $$c\\infty rdinate of F$$ is $$(\\frac{8}{3},\\frac{5}{3})$$ (ANS);  c) Now;$$N(-1,0)\\Rightarrow \\vec{AN}=\\vec{ON}-\\vec{OA}$$;=$$(\\binom{-1}{0})-(\\binom{-1}{4})$$;=$$(\\binom{0}{-4})$$;And ;$$\\vec{EF}=\\vec{OF}-\\vec{OE}$$;=$$\\binom{\\frac{8}{3}}{\\frac{5}{3}}-\\binom{\\frac{8}{3}}{\\frac{17}{3}}=(\\binom{0}{\\frac{-12}{3}})$$;=$$\\binom{0}{-4}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\vec{AN}=\\vec{EF}$$;Therefore  AN and EF are of same length and AN is parallel to EF, hence AEFN is a parallelogram (shown).;$$AN=\\sqrt{0^2+4^2}=4$$;perpendicular Distance between AN and EF,;d = $$\\frac{8}{3}-(-1)=\\frac{11}{3}$$; therefore area of AEFN = (AN)(d);= $$(4)\\frac{11}{3}$$;=$$\\frac{44}{3}units^2$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (153,'199700103016','$$\\vec{OA}-=a, \\vec{OB}-=b, \\vec{OC}-=a+2b$$;img;If;$$\\frac{AD}{AB}=p \\Rightarrow  \\frac{(AD)}{(DB)}= \\frac{p}{(1-p)}$$ and ;$$ \\frac{(OD)}{(OC)}=q \\Rightarrow \\frac{( OD)}{(DC)}= \\frac{q}{(1-q)}$$;  By ratio theorem,;a) $$\\vec{OD}=\\frac{1}{(p+(1-p))}[p\\vec{OB}+(1-p)\\vec{OA}]$$;=$$p(b)+(1-p)(a)$$;=pb + (1 - p)a (ANS);b)   $$\\vec{OD}=q\\vec{OC}=q(a+2b)$$;= qa + 2qb (ANS);By equating the two expressions for $$\\vec{OD}$$ we have,;$$\\vec{OD}=(1-p)a+pb=qa+2qb$$;$$1-p=q$$ …… (1);$$p=2q$$ ……..(2);(1) + (2) yields, 1 = 3q;therefore ;q= $$\\frac{1}{3}$$;Substitute q = $$\\frac{1}{3}$$ into (2), ;p= 2q ;= $$\\frac{2}{3}$$; Hence p = $$\\frac{2}{3}$$ and q = $$\\frac{1}{3}$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (154,'199700103017','i)$$f(x) \\mapsto  \\frac{ (3x-1)}{(x-2)},x\\neq 2$$;$$g(x) \\mapsto \\frac{ (2x-1)}{(x-3)},x\\neq 3$$;Therefore;$$fg(x)=f[g(x)]=f(\\frac{ (2x-1)}{(x-3)})= \\frac{ (3(\\frac{ (2x-1)}{(x-3)})-1)}{(( \\frac{ (2x-1)}{(x-3)})-2)}$$;= $$\\frac{ (3(2x-1)-(x-3))}{((2x-1)-2(x-3))}$$;= $$\\frac{ (6x-3-x+3)}{(2x-1-2x+6)}$$;= $$\\frac{5x}{5}$$;= $$x$$;therefore;fg(x) = x or $$fg:x \\mapsto  x$$ (SHOWN);ii)$$f^{-1}(x)=g(x)$$;$$f^{-1}(5)=g(5)= \\frac{ (2(5)-1)}{(5-3)}= \\frac{9}{2}$$;= 4.5 (ANS);$$g^{-1}(x)=f(x)$$;$$g^{-1}(4)=f(4)= \\frac{ (3(4)-1)}{(4-2)}=1\\frac{1}{2}$$;= 5.5 (ANS);$$ffg(x)=f[fg(x)]=f(x)$$;$$ffg(7)=f(7)= \\frac{ (3(7)-1)}{(7-2)}= \\frac{20}{5}$$;= 4 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (155,'199700103018','To sketch 3y = 4x + 2 and 3y = |4x - 8|, tabulate the point s from x = - 1 to x = 4 inclusively as summarized in the following table.;img;Graph of 3y = 4x + 2 and 3y = |4x - 8|;img;To solve the two simultaneous equations, we find the intersecting point  of the two curves on the graph. From the graph, the intersecting point  is $$(0.75,\\frac{5}{3})$$;Hence the solution is (x,y) = $$(0.75,\\frac{5}{3})$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (156,'199700104001','a) i) Remainder of $$x^3-ax+a^2$$;when x = 2 is ;$$f(2)=2^3-2a+a^2 = a^2-2a+8$$ ……(1);Similarly remainder of $$ax^3-x^2-17$$ is;$$g(2)=8a+4-17=8a-13$$ ……. (2);Now;f(2) = g(2);$$\\Rightarrow a^2-2a+8=8a-13$$;$$\\Rightarrow a^2-10a+21=0$$;$$(a-3)(a-7)=0$$;therefore a = 3 or a =7 (ANS);ii) When a = 3, remainder is given by;f(2) = g(2) =8(3) -13 = 11 (ANS);a = 7, remainder is given by;f(2) = g(2) =8(7) -13 = 43 (ANS);b) To find x-coordinate of each of the three point s of intersection, solve the simultaneous equations.;$$y=6x^2-5$$ ……… (1);$$y=17x-\\frac{6}{x}$$ …….. (2); (1) - (2) yields,;$$6x^2-5-17x+\\frac{6}{x}=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 6x^2-17x^2-5x+6=0$$;let $$f(x)=6x^2-17x^2-5x+6$$;by trial and error, we find that;$$f(\\frac{1}{2})=6(\\frac{1}{2})^2-17(\\frac{1}{2})^2-5(\\frac{1}{2})+6=0$$;therefore $$(x-\\frac{1}{2})$$ or $$(2x - 1)$$ is a factor of f(x).;img;therefore ;$$f(x)=6x^2-17x^2-5x+6$$;=$$(2x-1)(3x^2-7x-6)$$;=$$(3x+2)(x-3)(2x-1)$$;$$\\Rightarrow 6x^2-17x^2-5x+6=(3x+2)(x-3)(2x-1)=0$$;and hence ;$$x=\\frac{2}{3},\\frac{1}{2} or 3$$ (ANS);c) To find k, we attempt to factorize $$x^3-5x^2+12$$ into a linear factor and a quadratic factor.;Let $$g(x)=x^3-5x^2+12$$;By trial and error,;$$g(2)=2^3-5(2)^2+12=8-20+12=0$$;therefore (x - 2) is a factor of g(x);img;Hence ;$$g(x)=x^3-5x^2+12$$;=$$(x-2)(x^2-3x-6)$$;If $$x^2-3x+k$$ is a factor of $$x^3-5x^2+12$$ then it must be $$x^2-3x-6$$;therefore k = - 6 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (157,'199700104002','a) Let a be the first term and d be the common difference of the A.P.;$$\\Rightarrow T_10=10th term of the AP=a+9d=40$$;$$S_10=Sum of the first 10 terms of the AP=5(2a+9d)=265$$;Now;$$a+9d=40$$ ……..(1);$$2a+9d=53$$ ……(2); (2) - (1) yield a = 53 - 40 = 13;When a = 13,; $$d=\\frac{ (40-a)}{9}=\\frac{ (40-13)}{9}=\\frac{27}{9}=3$$;therefore first term of A.P, a = 13;common difference of A.P, d = 3;Hence sum of the first 20 terms of the A.P is given by;$$S_20=\\frac{20}{2}(2a+19d)=10(26+57)$$;= 830 (ANS);b) Let a be the first term and r be the common difference of the G.P.;$$\\Rightarrow T_1=a=100$$;$$T_2=ar=120=\\frac{120}{a}=\\frac{120}{100}=1.20$$;To find k, we find the kth term of the G.P which is ;$$T_k=ar^{k-1}=100(1.2)^{k-1}$$;To find k such that; $$T_k<5000$$;$$100(1.2)^{k-1}<5000$$;$$\\Rightarrow (1.2)^{k-1}<50$$;$$\\Rightarrow (k-1)\\log (1.2)<\\log 50$$;$$\\Rightarrow (k-1)(0.07918)<1.69897$$;$$\\Rightarrow k<\\frac{1.69897}{0.07918}+1$$;$$\\Rightarrow k<22.46$$;therefore largest integer for k is k = 22 (ANS);Hence the sum of the first k(= 22) terms of the G.P is;$$S_22=a\\frac{ (r^k-1)}{(r-1)}$$;=$$100(\\frac{ ((1.2)^{(k-1)}}{(1.2-1)})$$;=$$100(\\frac{54.2061}{0.2})$$;=27103.07;$$\\approx  27103$$ (ANS);c) Let a and r be the first term and common ratio of t he initial G.P.;Now;$$\\Rightarrow T_1=a=18$$;$$S_\\infty =\\frac{a}{(1-r)}=30$$;From which, we may write;a = 18;$$r=1-\\frac{a}{30}=1-1\\frac{8}{30}=1-\\frac{3}{5}=\\frac{2}{5}=0.4$$;EAch term of the initial G.P is squared to form a new geometrical progress. Now the new G.P has $$a^2$$ as the first term and $$r^2$$as the common ratio.;Hence the first term of the new G.P,;b = $$a^2=18^2=324$$;	common ratio of the new G.P, ;t = $$r^2=0.4^2=0.16$$  ;The sum to infinity of the new progression is thus;$$S_\\infty =\\frac{b}{(1-t)}= \\frac{324}{(1-0.16)}= \\frac{324}{0.84}=385.71$$; \\approx 386 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (158,'199700104003','a) i) Compute the values of xy and $$x^3$$ for each corresponding value of x and plot the graph of  xy versus $$x^3$$;img; From the graph, gradient of the line = $$-\\frac{Y}{Xz}=-\\frac{79}{5z}=-15.8$$;$$\\Rightarrow (xy-79)=-15.8(x^3-1)$$;$$\\Rightarrow xy=-15.8x^3+94.8$$;i.e $$y=-15.8x^2+\\frac{94.8}{x}$$ (ANS);ii) when  ; $$y=\\frac{60}{x} \\Rightarrow  xy=60$$;From the graph,;$$x^3=2.2\\Rightarrow x=(2.2)^{\\frac{1}{3}}$$;$$\\approx 1.30$$ (ANS);b) Now the line equation of (xy - x) against y is given by;$$ \\frac{ ((xy-x)-1)}{(y-2)}= \\frac{ (2-1)}{(1.5-2)}=- \\frac{1}{0.5}=-2$$;$$\\Rightarrow xy-x-1=-2y+4$$;$$\\Rightarrow xy+2y=x+5$$;$$\\Rightarrow y(x+2)=x+5$$;therefore; $$y=\\frac{ (x+5)}{(x+2)}$$;Hence c = 5 and d = 2 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (159,'199700104004','a) i) when t = 30, ;$$m=24e^{-0.02(20)}$$;=$$24e^{-0.6}$$;=$$24(0.5488)$$;=13.17 (ANS);ii) when t =0,;$$m=24e^0=24$$;therefore $$\\frac{1}{2}m(t=0)=\\frac{1}{2}(24)=12$$;Now;$$12=24e^{-0.02t}$$;$$\\Rightarrow e^{-0.02t}=\\frac{1}{2}$$;$$\\Rightarrow e^{0.02t}=2$$;$$\\Rightarrow 0.02t=\\ln 2$$;$$\\Rightarrow t=\\frac{ (\\ln 2)}{0.02}=50\\ln 2=50(0.693)$$=34.65 (ANS);iii) Rate at which mass is decreasing,;$$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d} m}{\\mathrm{d} t} =-24(0.02)e^{-0.02t}=-0.48e^{-0.02t}$$;At t=50,;$$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d} m}{\\mathrm{d} t} =-0.48e^{-0.02(50)}$$;=$$-0.48e^{-1}$$;=$$0.48(0.3679)$$;= -0.18 (ANS);b) $$\\lg (20+5x)-\\lg (10-x)=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\lg (\\frac{ (20+5x)}{(10-x)})=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{ (20+5x)}{(10-x)}=10^1=10$$;$$\\Rightarrow 20+5x=100-10x$$;$$\\Rightarrow 15x=80$$;$$\\Rightarrow x=\\frac{80}{15}=\\frac{16}{3}=5 \\frac{1}{3}$$ (ANS);c) if x = \\lg  a then $$a=10^x$$;Now;$$10^{2x+1}-7(10^x)=26$$;$$\\Rightarrow 10a^2-7a-26=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (a-2)(10a+13)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow a=2 or a=-1.3$$ (rejected);Hence a = 2 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (160,'199700104005','a) i) $$2\\cos 2x=4\\sin x+3$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2(1-2\\sin ^2x)=4\\sin x+3$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2-4\\sin ^2x=4\\sin x+3$$;$$\\Rightarrow 4\\sin ^2x+4\\sin x+1=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (2\\sin x+1)^2=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2\\sin x+1=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\sin x=-\\frac{1}{2}$$;hence $$x=210^{\\circ},330^{\\circ}$$ (ANS);ii) $$\\sin (y+30^{\\circ})=3\\cos y$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\sin y\\cos 30^{\\circ}+\\cos y\\sin 30^{\\circ}=3\\cos y$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\sqrt{\\frac{3}{2}}\\sin y+\\frac{1}{2}\\cos y=3\\cos y$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\sqrt{\\frac{3}{2}}\\sin y=\\frac{5}{2}\\cos y$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\tan y=\\frac{5}{\\sqrt3}=2.8868$$;therefore $$y=70.9^{\\circ},250.9^{\\circ}$$ (ANS); b) Let ;$$3\\cos x-4\\sin x-=R\\cos (x+\\alpha )$$;$$\\Rightarrow 3\\cos x-4\\sin x=R\\cos \\alpha \\cos x-R\\sin \\alpha \\sin x$$;$$R\\cos \\alpha =3$$ ……(1);$$R\\sin \\alpha =4$$ …….(2);$$(1)^2+(2)^2$$ yield;$$R^2(\\cos ^2\\alpha +\\sin ^2\\alpha )=R^2=3^2+4^2=5^2$$;therefore R = 5;(2) + (1) yield;$$\\tan \\alpha =\\frac{4}{3}\\Rightarrow \\alpha =\\tan ^{-1}(\\frac{4}{3})=0.927rad$$;therefore;$$3\\cos x-4\\sin x=5\\cos (x+0.927)$$;i) The point  on the curve at which y = 1 is given by;$$3\\cos x-4\\sin x=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow 5\\cos (x+0.927)=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\cos (x+0.927)=\\frac{1}{5}$$;$$\\Rightarrow x+0.927=1.369$$;$$\\Rightarrow x=0.422rad$$;There the coordinate of the point  is (0.422,1) (ANS);ii)$$y=3\\cos x-4\\sin x=5\\cos (x+0.927)$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=-5\\sin (x+0.927)$$;therefore  \\sin (x + 0.927) = 0 at stationary point  of the curve;$$\\Rightarrow x+0.927=\\pi $$;$$\\Rightarrow x=\\pi -0.927=2.215$$;when x = 2.215;$$y = 5\\cos (x + 0.927) = 5\\cos \\pi  =- 5$$;therefore the coordinates of the stationary point  for $$0\\leq x\\leq \\pi $$ is (2.215, - 5). (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (161,'199700104006','a) Let z = \\sin  x and $$z^2=\\sin ^2x$$Now ;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} }{\\mathrm{d} x}(z^2)=2z\\frac{\\mathrm{d}z}{\\mathrm{d} x}; \\frac{\\mathrm{d}z}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\cos x$$;therefore $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} }{\\mathrm{d} x}(\\sin ^2x)=2\\sin x\\cos x=\\sin 2x$$ (ANS);b) $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} }{\\mathrm{d} x}(\\frac{ (2x-3)}{(x+5)})= \\frac{ ((x+5)(2)-(2x-3)(1))}{(x+5)^2}$$;Therefore $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} }{\\mathrm{d} x}\\frac{ ((2x-3)}{(x+5))}= \\frac{ (2x+10-2x-3)}{(x+5)^2}=\\frac{13}{(x+5)^2}=\\frac{k}{(x+5)^2}$$;hence k = 13 (ANS);c) $$y^2=x^2+2xy+8$$when x = 2;$$y^2=4+4y+8$$;$$\\Rightarrow y^2-4y-12=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (y-6)(y+2)=0$$;therefore y = +6 or y = - 2;Hence the two point s are A(2, - 2)and B(2, 6) ;Now by differentiating the equation, we have;$$2y\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=2x+2x\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}+2y$$;$$\\Rightarrow (y-x)\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=y+x$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{ (y+x)}{(y-x)}$$;Thus for A(2, - 2) the gradient at A is ;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{-2+2}{-2-2}=0$$ (ANS);Similarly for B(2, 6) the gradient at B is;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{ (6+2)}{(6-2)}= \\frac{8}{4}=2$$ (ANS);d)i) $$y=\\frac{c}{(1+2x)^2}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{ (-2c)}{(1+2x)^3(2)}=- \\frac{ (4c)}{(1+2x)^3}$$ (ANS);ii) When x increases from 1 to 1 + p,;$$gradx = (1+p)-1=p$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}$$ at x = 1 is given by $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=-\\frac{ (4c)}{(3^3)}=- \\frac{ (4c)}{27}$$;Thus by applying,; $$grad y\\approx (\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x})grad x$$;for small increment in x, incremental change in y is given by;$$grad y\\approx (-\\frac{ (4c)}{27})p=\\frac{ (-4cp)}{27}$$;Given;$$grad y=-\\frac{ (8p)}{3}\\Rightarrow -\\frac{ (8p)}{3}=\\frac{ (-4cp)}{27}$$;$$\\Rightarrow c=(\\frac{8}{3})(\\frac{27}{4})=18$$ (ANS)');
