INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (163,'199700104008','i) $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d}x }{\\mathrm{d} t}=4t-\\frac{9}{t^2} , \\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} t}=2$$;Therefore,;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} t}}{\\frac{\\mathrm{d} x}{\\mathrm{d} t}}$$;=$$\\frac{2}{(4t-\\frac{9}{t^2})}$$;=$$ \\frac{ (2t^2)}{(4t^2-9)}$$ (ANS);ii) To find equation of tangent at (13, - 3), need to know the gradient of the tangent at the point  ;Now y = 2t -  5 =- 3;t = 1;Therefore gradient of tangent at (13, - 3);=$$ \\frac{ (y-(-3))}{(x-13)}=-\\frac{2}{5}$$;$$\\Rightarrow 5y+15=-2x+26$$;$$\\Rightarrow 5y=-2x+11$$;When y = 0,;$$x=\\frac{ (11-5y)}{2}=1\\frac{1}{2}=5.5$$;Thus the tangent meets the x - axis (i.e y = 0) at point  (5.5, 0) (ANS);iii) Now $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} x}{\\mathrm{d} y}=\\frac{1}{(\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x})} = \\frac{ (4t^2-9)}{(2t^2)}$$;Thus ;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} x}{\\mathrm{d} y}=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{ (4t^2-9)}{(2t^2)}=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 4t^2-9=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow t^2=\\frac{9}{4}$$;$$\\Rightarrow t= +-\\frac{3}{2}$$;when $$t=-\\frac{3}{2},$$;$$x=4(-\\frac{3}{2})+\\frac{9 }{ (-\\frac{3}{2})}=-6-6=-12$$;$$y=2(-\\frac{3}{2})-5=-3-5=-8$$;therefore (x, y) = (- 12, 8) at $$t=-\\frac{3}{2}$$;$$t=\\frac{3}{2}$$;$$x=4(\\frac{3}{2})+\\frac{9 }{ (\\frac{3}{2})}=12$$;$$y=2(\\frac{3}{2})-5=3-5=-2$$;therefore (x, y) = (12, - 2) at $$t=\\frac{3}{2}$$;Hence the coordinates of each of the point s on the curve at which the tangent to the curve is parallel to the y-axis are (- 12, - 8) and (12, - 2) respectively. (ANS);iv) $$(4t+\\frac{9}{t})+(2t-5)=16$$;$$\\Rightarrow 6t-21+\\frac{9}{t}=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 6t^2-21t+3=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2t^2-7t+1=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (2t-1)(t-3)=0$$;therefore ;$$t=\\frac{1}{2} or t=3$$ (ANS);v) Now;$$x=\\frac{4t+9}{t}$$ ……(1);$$y=2t-5$$ ……...(2);From (2) we have ;$$ \\frac{ (y+5)}{2}=t$$;By substituting $$\\frac{ (y+5)}{2}=t$$ into(1) we have;$$x=4\\frac{ ((y+5)}{2)+9}{(\\frac{ (y+5)}{2})}$$;$$\\Rightarrow x=\\frac{ (2(y+5)^2+18)}{(y+5)}$$;$$\\Rightarrow x=2\\frac{ ((y+5)^2+9)}{(y+5)}$$;x =$$\\frac{ (2y^2+20y+68)}{(y+5)}$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (164,'199800101001','4xy + 5 = 0, ……(1);3y + x = 1 ………(2);From (2);x = 1 - 3y......(3);Sub (3) into (1) , we have;$$4(1-3y)y+5=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 4y-12y^2+5=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 12y^2-4y-5=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (2y+1)(6y-5)=0$$;Therefore;$$y=-\\frac{1}{2} or y=\\frac{5}{6}$$;Sub. $$y=-\\frac{1}{2}$$ into (3),;$$x=1+3(\\frac{1}{2})=\\frac{5}{2}$$;Sub. $$y=\\frac{5}{6}$$ \\int o (3),;$$x=1-3(\\frac{5}{6})=-\\frac{3}{2}$$;therefore the solutions are $$(\\frac{5}{2},-\\frac{1}{2})$$ and $$(-\\frac{3}{2},\\frac{5}{6})$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (165,'199800101002','From;$$pq^2=144$$;$$\\Rightarrow p=\\frac{144}{q^2}$$;therefore;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} p}{\\mathrm{d} q}=144(\\frac{(-2)}{(q^3)})=\\frac{-288}{q^3}$$ (ANS);Now ;$$q=q_0=6, gradq=k$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} p}{\\mathrm{d} q}=\\frac{(-288)}{q^3}=\\frac{(-288)}{6^3}=\\frac{-4}{3}$$;therefore;$$gradp=\\frac{(-4)}{3} \\times  k = \\frac{(-4)}{3}k$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (166,'199800101003','To find P, solve the equations;$$y=2x$$;$$y=4\\sqrt x$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2x=4\\sqrt x$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2(\\sqrt x)(\\sqrt {x-2})=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\sqrt x=0$$(rejected) or $$\\sqrt x=2$$;x = 4;y = 2(4) = 8;therefore coordinates of P is (4, 8) (ANS);Volume generated;= $$\\pi \\int _0^4{(4\\sqrt x)^2-(2x)^2}dx$$;=$$\\pi \\int _0^4{16x-4x^2}dx$$;=$$4\\pi [2x^2-\\frac{ (x^3)}{3}]_0^4$$;=$$4\\pi [32-\\frac{64}{3}]$$;=$$\\frac{ (128\\pi )}{3}units^3$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (167,'199800101004','a) $$y=\\frac{ (3x-4)^5}{16}$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}= \\frac{ (5(3x-4)^4)}{16}(3) =\\frac{15}{16}(3x-4)^4$$;when x =  2;$$y=\\frac{ (2)^5}{16}=\\frac{32}{16}=2$$;$$(\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x})=\\frac{15}{16}(3x-4)^4=\\frac{15}{16}(2)^4=15$$;therefore equation of tangent to the curve at x = 2 is given by;$$ \\frac{ (y-2)}{(x-2)}=15$$;$$y=15x-28$$ (ANS);b)Now $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} x}{\\mathrm{d} t}=0.02\\frac{units}{s} $$;At x = 2,;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=15$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} t}=\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x} \\ast  \\frac{\\mathrm{d} x}{\\mathrm{d} t}=15 \\times  0.02=0.30 \\frac{units}{s}$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (168,'199800101005','a) $$4x^2-(c+2)x+c=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow 4x^2-(c+2)x+(c-1)=0$$;Now;$$D=(c+2)^2-4(4)(c-1)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (c^2+4c+4)-16c+16=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow c^2-12c+20=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (c-2)(c-10)=0$$;therefore c = 2 or c =10 (ANS);b) To intersect at two distinct points, then;$$ \\frac{16}{x}=k-x$$;$$\\Rightarrow x^2-kx+16=0$$;$$D=B^2-4AC=k^2-4(1)(16)>0$$;$$\\Rightarrow k^2>64$$;k > 8 or k < - 8 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (169,'199800101006','i) When particle comes to instan taneous rets at point  Q, then;$$5t-3t^2+2=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (2-t)(3t+1)=0$$;$$t=2 or t=-\\frac{1}{3}(N.A)$$;To find acceleration, we have,;$$a=\\frac{\\mathrm{d} v}{\\mathrm{d} t}=5-6t$$;therefore at point  Q,;acceleration = 5 - 6(2) =$$-7 ms^{-2}$$ (ANS);ii) The distance OQ is given by;$$s=\\int _0^2vdt=\\int _0^2(5t-3t^2+2)dt$$;=$$[\\frac{5}{2}t^2-t^3+2t]_0^2$$;=10 - 8 + 4;=6m (ANS);iii) In the time interval t = 2 to t =3, distance travelled by the particle is;$$s_2=\\int _2^3vdt=\\int _2^3(5t-3t^2+2)dt$$;=$$[\\frac{5}{2}t^2-t^3+2t]_2^3=(4\\frac{5}{2}-27+6)-6$$;=$$\\frac{3}{2}-6$$;= - 4.5m ;Thus total distance travelled in the time interval t = 0 to t = 3 is given by 6 + 4.5 or 10.5 m (ANS).');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (170,'199800101007','a) To find  term in x in the expansion of $$(x-\\frac{2}{x})^7$$, we solve for r so that $$T_r$$ is in x, i.e.,;$$7-2r=1 or r=\\frac{ (7-1)}{2}=3$$;Thus coefficient of x is given by; $$^7C_3(-2)^3=-280$$; (ANS);b)Now;$$(1-\\frac{x}{2})^8=1-8(\\frac{x}{2})+28(\\frac{x}{2})^2-56(\\frac{x}{2})^3+...$$;=$$1-4x+7x^2-7x^3+...$$;Thus $$(2+5x)(1-\\frac{x}{2})^8=(2+5x)(1-4x+7x^2-7x^3+...)$$;and terms in $$x^3$$ is given by;$$2(-7x^3)+5x(7x^2)=-14x^3+35x^3=21x^3$$;Hence the coefficient of $$x^3$$ in the expansion of $$(2+5x)(1-\\frac{x}{2})^8$$ is 21. (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (171,'199800101008','L.H.S = $$\\frac{1}{(1+\\sin \\theta )}+ \\frac{1}{(1-\\sin \\theta )}$$;=$$ \\frac{ (1-\\sin \\theta )}{((1-\\sin \\theta )(1+\\sin \\theta ))}+ \\frac{ (1+\\sin \\theta )}{((1-\\sin \\theta )(1+\\sin \\theta ))}$$;=$$ \\frac{2}{(1-\\sin ^2\\theta )}$$;=$$ \\frac{2}{(\\cos ^2\\theta )}$$;=$$2sec^2\\theta $$ (SHOWN)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (172,'199800101009','$$f(x)=2x^2-6x+7$$;=$$2(x^2-3x)+7$$;=$$2[(x-\\frac{3}{2})^2-\\frac{9}{4}]+7$$;Or;$$f(x)=2(x-\\frac{3}{2})^2+\\frac{5}{2}$$;Now when x = 0, f(0) = 7;x = 4, ;$$f(4)=2(\\frac{5}{2})^2+\\frac{5}{2}=15$$;But minimum value of f(x) occurs at $$x=\\frac{3}{2}$$ whose value is given by;$$f(\\frac{3}{2})=\\frac{5}{2}$$;Therefore range of the function $$f:x \\mapsto  2x^2-6x+7$$ for the domain $$0\\leq x\\leq 4$$ is $$2 \\frac{1}{2}\\leq f(x)\\leq 15$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (173,'199800101010','a) $$y=(2x+1)(4-x^2)$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=2(4-x^2)+(-2x)(2x+1)$$;=$$8-2x^2-4x^2-2x$$;=$$8-2x-6x^2$$ ;Stationary point  of curve y are obtained by setting ;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 3x^2+x-4=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (3x+4)(x-1)=0$$;$$x=-\\frac{4}{3} or x=1$$;when $$x=-\\frac{4}{3}$$, ;$$y=(1-\\frac{8}{3})(4-\\frac{16}{9})=-\\frac{100}{27}$$;when x = 1, y = (3)(3) = 9;Now;	$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d}^{2} y}{\\mathrm{d} x^{2}}=-2-12x$$;when $$x=-\\frac{4}{3}$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d}^{2} y}{\\mathrm{d} x^{2}}=-2-12(-\\frac{4}{3})=-2+16=14>0$$;and hence $$(-\\frac{4}{3},-\\frac{100}{27})$$ is a minimum point  of the curve. (ANS);When x = 1,;$$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d}^{2} y}{\\mathrm{d} x^{2}}=-2-12(1)=-14<0$$;and hence (1, 9) is a maximum point of the curve. (ANS);b)9x + 8y = 720 or 8y = 720 - 9x....(1);Area, A, in terms of x and y is given by;$$A=6xy=\\frac{ (3x)}{4(8y)}= \\frac{ (3x)}{4(720-9x)}$$;$$A=\\frac{3}{4}(720-9x^2)$$ (SHOWN);To find x such that A is a maximum, we set;$$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d} A}{\\mathrm{d} x} =0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 720-18x=0$$;$$x=40 and y=\\frac{1}{8}(720-360)=45$$;and check that;$$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d}^{2} y}{\\mathrm{d} x^{2}}=-\\frac{27}{2}<0$$;Thus when x = 40 m and y = 45 m, the area A is a maximum. (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (174,'199800101011','a) Gradient of line BC = gradient of line AD;m = gradient of line BC = $$\\frac{ (4-12)}{(6-2)}=- \\frac{8}{4}=-2$$;Therefore equation of line BC is ;$$ \\frac{ (y-0)}{(x-13)}=m=-2$$ where $$C -= (13,0)$$;$$\\Rightarrow  y=-2x+26$$ ….equation of line BC (ANS);Gradient of line AX;= $$-\\frac{1}{m}$$; With $$A -= (2,12)$$, equation of line AX is thus given by;$$y-12=-\\frac{1}{((-2))(x-2)}$$;$$or y=\\frac{1}{2}x+11$$ …. Equation of line AX (ANS);b)$$x_b=2$$;and thus y-coordinate of B, $$y_b$$ is given by ;$$y_b=-2x_b+26=26-4=22$$;therefore ;$$B -=(2,22)$$ (ANS);X is obtained by solving the simultaneous equations of AX and BC,;$$y=\\frac{1}{2}x+11$$;$$y=-2x+26$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{2}x+11=-2x+26$$;$$\\Rightarrow x+22=-4x+52$$;$$\\Rightarrow 5x=30$$;x = 6 and y=26 - 2(6) =14;Hence;$$X -= (6, 14)$$ (ANS) ;c)Length AD ;= $$\\sqrt{(12-4)^2+(6-2)^2}$$;=$$\\sqrt{8^2+4^2}$$;=$$(4)\\sqrt{2^2+1^2} = 4\\sqrt 5 units$$;Length BC ;= $$\\sqrt{(22-0)^2+(13-2)^2}$$;=$$\\sqrt{22^2+11^2}$$;=$$(11)\\sqrt{2^2+1^2} = 11\\sqrt 5 units$$;Therefore ratio BC : AD;= $$11\\sqrt 5:4\\sqrt 5$$;=$$11:4$$;=$$\\frac{11}{4}:1$$;=$$2.75:1$$ (ANS);=$$n:1$$;where n = 2.75;d) Length AX = $$\\sqrt{(14-12)^2+(6-2)^2}$$;=$$\\sqrt{2^2+4^2}$$;=$$(2)\\sqrt{2^2+1^2}$$;=$$2\\sqrt5 units$$ (ANS); Area of trapezium ABCD;= $$\\frac{1}{2}(AX)(AD+BC)$$;=$$\\frac{1}{2}(AX)(n+1)(AD)$$;=$$\\frac{1}{2}(2\\sqrt 5)(3.75)(4\\sqrt 5)$$;=$$(3.75)(4)(5)$$;=$$75units^2$$(ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (175,'199800101012','a) i)$$2\\sin x+3\\cos x=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2\\sin x=-3\\cos x$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\tan x=\\frac{\\sin x}{\\cos x}=-\\frac{3}{2}=-1.5$$;$$x=\\tan ^{-1}(-1.5)$$;  Therefore;$$x=\\pi -\\tan ^{-1}(-1.5) or x=2\\pi -\\tan ^{-1}(-1.5)$$;$$or x=180^{\\circ} -56.31^{\\circ}  or x=360^{\\circ} -56.31^{\\circ} $$;i.e $$or x=123.69^{\\circ}  or x=303.69^{\\circ} $$ (ANS);ii)$$2\\tan ^2y=5secy+1$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2(sec^2y-1)=5secy+1$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2sec^2y-5secy-3=0$$;$$(secy-3)(2secy+1)=0$$;$$secy=3 or secy=-\\frac{1}{2}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\cos y=\\frac{1}{3} or \\cos y=-2(rejected)$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\cos y=\\frac{1}{3}$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=\\cos ^{-1}(\\frac{1}{3}) or y=2\\pi -\\cos ^{-1}(\\frac{1}{3})$$;$$y=70.53^{\\circ}  or y=289.47^{\\circ} $$;therefore;$$y=70.53^{\\circ}  or y=289.47^{\\circ} $$ (ANS);b)$$2\\sin (\\frac{ (\\pi z)}{4})=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\sin (\\frac{ (\\pi z)}{4})=0.5$$;$$\\Rightarrow (\\frac{ (\\pi z)}{4})=\\frac{\\pi }{6},\\pi -\\frac{\\pi }{6},2\\pi +\\frac{\\pi }{6},3\\pi -\\frac{\\pi }{6},...$$;$$\\Rightarrow (\\frac{ (\\pi z)}{4})=\\frac{\\pi }{6},\\frac{ (5\\pi )}{6},\\frac{ (13\\pi )}{6},\\frac{ (17\\pi )}{6},...$$;$$\\Rightarrow z=\\frac{4}{6},\\frac{20}{6},\\frac{52}{6},\\frac{68}{6},...$$;i.e $$z=\\frac{2}{3},\\frac{10}{3},\\frac{26}{3}$$ for z between 0 and 10;Hence z = 0.67, 3.33 and 8.67 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (176,'199800101013','a) Arc AXB = $$r\\theta $$ = (6)(2.4) = 14.4 cm (ANS);b) Area of sector OAXB = $$\\frac{1}{2}r^2\\theta $$;= $$\\frac{1}{2}(6)^2(2.4)$$;=$$43.2cm^2$$ (ANS);c) Length, AB = $$2(6)\\sin (\\frac{2.4}{2})$$;=$$12\\sin (1.2)$$;$$\\approx 11.2cm$$ (ANS);	d) Similarly, the angle ACB can be found using $$L=2r\\sin (\\frac{\\theta }{2})$$;since length L and r are known to us;img;Now;$$L=2r\\sin (\\frac{\\theta }{2})$$;$$\\Rightarrow 11.1845=2(10)\\sin (\\frac{\\theta }{2})$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\sin (\\frac{\\theta }{2})=0.5592$$;$$\\Rightarrow\\frac{\\theta }{2}=\\sin ^{-1}(0.5592)=0.59345$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\theta =1.1869$$;$$\\approx 1.187 rad$$ (ANS);e) Arc length AYB = $$r\\theta $$=(10)(1.187)=11.87 cm;Thus perimeter of the shaded region ;= arc length AYB + arc length AXB;=11.87 + 14.4 ;=26.27 cm (ANS);f) Area of sector OAXB = $$43.2 cm^2$$ [from (ii)]];Area of triangle OAB = $$\\frac{1}{2}(6)^2\\sin (2.4)$$;  =$$12.16cm^2$$;therefore Area of segment AXB = 43.2 - 12.16 = $$31.04 cm^2$$  ;Similarly, Area of sector CAYB;= $$\\frac{1}{2}r^2\\theta =\\frac{1}{2}(10)^2(1.187)$$;=$$59.35cm^2$$  ;Area of triangle CAB ;= $$\\frac{1}{2}(10)^2\\sin (1.187)$$; =$$46.36cm^2$$;therefore area of segment AYB = 53.35 - 46.36 = $$12.99 cm^2$$;Hence area of shaded region = 31.04 - 12.99 =$$18.05 cm^2$$ (ANS);img; In general, area of shaded region in the diagram is given by;area = $$\\frac{1}{2}r^2\\theta -\\frac{1}{2}r^2\\sin \\theta $$; =$$\\frac{1}{2}r^2(\\theta -\\sin \\theta )$$');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (177,'199800101014','a) $$\\vec{OA}-=\\binom{2}{3}, \\vec{OB}-=\\binom{5}{1}$$;$$\\vec{OC}=\\vec{OA}+\\vec{OB}=\\binom{2}{3}+\\binom{5}{1}=\\binom{7}{4}$$;Thus;$$\\vec{AB}=\\vec{OB}-\\vec{OA}=\\binom{5}{1}-\\binom{2}{3}=\\binom{3}{-2}$$;$$\\vec{AC}=\\vec{OB}-=\\binom{5}{1}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\vec{AB}\\ast \\vec{AC}=\\binom{3}{-2}\\ast \\binom{5}{1}$$;       = 15 - 2 = 13 (ANS);But ;$$\\Rightarrow \\vec{AB}\\ast \\vec{AC}=(AB)(AC)\\cos (CAB)$$;$$\\Rightarrow 13=(\\sqrt{3^2+2^2})(\\sqrt{5^2+1^2})\\cos (CAB)$$;$$\\cos (CAB)= \\frac{13}{(\\sqrt{13}\\sqrt{26})}= \\frac{13}{(13\\sqrt2)}= \\frac{1}{\\sqrt2}$$ (ANS);Therefore ;$$CAB = 45^{\\circ} $$ (ANS);b)$$\\vec{OP}=p$$;$$\\vec{OQ}=q$$;$$\\vec{OR}=4p$$;$$\\vec{OM}=\\frac{1}{2}(\\vec{OP}+\\vec{OQ})=\\frac{1}{2}(p+q)$$;Therefore ;$$\\vec{OS}=\\frac{8}{5}(\\vec{OM}=\\frac{8}{5}\\ast \\frac{1}{2}(p+q)= \\frac{4}{5}(p+q)$$ (ANS);and ;$$\\vec{QR}=\\vec{OR}-\\vec{OQ}=4p-q$$ (ANS);Now;$$\\vec{QS}=\\vec{OS}-\\vec{OQ}$$;=$$\\frac{4}{5}(p+q)-q$$;=$$\\frac{1}{5}(4p+4q-5q)$$;=$$ \\frac{1}{5}(4p-q)$$;$$\\vec{SR}=\\vec{OR}-\\vec{OS}$$;=$$4p-\\frac{4}{5}(p+q)$$;=$$ \\frac{4}{5}(5p-p-q)$$;=$$ \\frac{4}{5}(4p-q)$$;Therefore ;$$\\vec{QS}=\\frac{1}{4}[\\frac{4}{5}(4p-q)]= \\frac{1}{4}\\vec{SR}$$;since $$\\frac{QS}{SR}$$ and S is a common point , QSR is thus a straight line and hence S lies on R (proved);Now;$$\\vec{QS}=\\frac{1}{4}\\vec{SR}$$;$$\\Rightarrow QS=\\frac{1}{4}SR$$;i.e QS:SR = 1:4 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (178,'199800101015','$$y=\\frac{x^2}{9}+\\frac{x}{6}+k$$;Area of region A = $$\\int _0^6ydx=23 units^2$$;$$\\Rightarrow area A=\\int _0^6\\frac{ (x^2)}{9}+\\frac{x}{6}+kdx$$;=$$[\\frac{1}{27}x^3+\\frac{1}{12}x^2+kx]_0^6$$;=$$8 + 3 + 6k$$;=$$11 + 6k$$;$$\\Rightarrow 11+6k=23$$;	Therefore;$$k=\\frac{ (23-11)}{6}$$;=$$\\frac{12}{6}$$;= 2 (SHOWN); i) Now $$y=\\frac{x^2}{9}+\\frac{x}{6}+2$$;Coordinates of P is $$P -= (6, 7)$$ and;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{2}{9x}+\\frac{1}{6}$$;Gradient of tangent at P = $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{2}{9}(6)+ \\frac{1}{6}=\\frac{3}{2}$$;Gradient of normal at P = $$-\\frac{1}{(\\frac{3}{2})}=-\\frac{2}{3}$$ ;Therefore equation of normal PQ is thus given by;$$y-7=-\\frac{2}{3}(x-6)$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=-\\frac{2}{3}x+11$$ … (line PQ);Coordinates of is thus $$Q -= (0, 11)$$ (ANS);img;ii) Area of trapezium QXPQ;= $$\\frac{1}{2}(6)(OQ+PX)$$;=$$3(11+7)$$;=$$54units^2$$;Therefore area of B = area of trapezium QXPQ - area of A = 54 - 23 = $$31 units^2$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (179,'199800101016','$$f:x\\mapsto 3x-a$$;$$g:x\\mapsto \\frac{b}{x},x\\neq 0$$;$$\\Rightarrow f^2(x)=3(3x-a)-a=9x-4a$$;$$fg(x)=f(g(x))=3(\\frac{b}{x})-a=\\frac{(3b)}{x}-a,x\\neq 0$$;Now;$$f^2(2)=10\\Rightarrow 18-4a=10$$;$$fg(2)=16\\Rightarrow \\frac{ (3b)}{2}-a=16$$;$$a=\\frac{ (18-10)}{4}=\\frac{8}{4}=2$$;$$b=\\frac{2}{3}(16+a)= \\frac{2}{3}(16+2)=12$$;Therefore a =2 and b = 12 (ANS);img;img;Now see graph of curves 2y = |x - 2| and y =x+|2x|;From the graphs, the intersection occur at, x = - 2 and x = 0.3;Therefore solution to equation $$\\frac{(|x-2|)}{2}=x+|2x|$$;x = - 2 and x = 0.3 (ANS)');
