INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (188,'199800102008','i) The points of intersection of curve with 5y = x - 2 are given by;$$x=\\frac{t+1}{t-1}, y=\\frac{t-1}{t-1}  where  t\\neq 0$$;$$5(\\frac{t-1}{t-1})=(\\frac{t+1}{t-1})-2$$;$$\\Rightarrow 5t-\\frac{5}{t}-5=t+\\frac{1}{t}-3$$;$$\\Rightarrow 4t-2-\\frac{6}{t}=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2t^2-t-3=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (2t-3)(t+1)=0$$;Thus t = - 1 or t = $$\\frac{3}{2}$$ (ANS);ii) $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=1+\\frac{1}{t^2}=\\frac{ (1+t^2)}{t^2}$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} x}{\\mathrm{d} t}=1-\\frac{1}{t^2}=\\frac{ (t^2-1)}{t^2}$$;Therefore;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{\\frac{\\mathrm{d}y }{\\mathrm{d} t}}{\\frac{\\mathrm{d}x }{\\mathrm{d} t}}=\\frac{\\frac{ (1+t^2)}{(t^2)}}{( \\frac{ (t^2-1)}{t^2})}$$;=$$\\frac{ (t^2+1)}{(t^2-1)}$$ (ANS);iii) Now;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{-5}{3}$$;$$\\Rightarrow\\frac{ (t^2+1)}{(t^2-1)}= \\frac{ (-5)}{3}$$;$$\\Rightarrow 5t^2-5=-3t^2-3$$;$$\\Rightarrow 8t^2=2$$;$$\\Rightarrow t^2=\\frac{1}{4}$$;$$t=\\pm \\frac{1}{2}$$;When $$t=-\\frac{1}{2}$$,;$$x=-\\frac{1}{2}-2-1=-\\frac{7}{2}$$;$$y=-\\frac{1}{2}+2-1=\\frac{1}{2}$$;When $$t=\\frac{1}{2}$$,;$$x=\\frac{1}{2}+2-1=\\frac{3}{2}$$;$$y=\\frac{1}{2}-2-1=-\\frac{5}{2}$$;Thus $$P-=(\\frac{ (-7)}{2},\\frac{1}{2})$$;and $$Q-=(\\frac{3}{2},-\\frac{5}{2})$$;Hence mid-point of line;$$PQ-=[\\frac{1}{2}(-\\frac{7}{2}+\\frac{3}{2}),\\frac{1}{2}(\\frac{1}{2}-\\frac{5}{2})]-=(-1,-1)$$ (ANS);iv);img;img v) $$x=t+\\frac{1}{t}-1\\Rightarrow t+\\frac{1}{t}=x+1\\Rightarrow t=\\frac{1}{2}[(x+1)+(y+1)]=\\frac{1}{2}(x+y+2)$$;$$y=t-\\frac{1}{t}-1\\Rightarrow t-\\frac{1}{t}=y+1\\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{t}=\\frac{1}{2}[(x+1)-(y+1)]=\\frac{1}{2}(x-y)$$;Now;$$t(\\frac{1}{t})=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{4}(x+y+2)(x-y)=1$$;Hence (x - y)(x + y +2) = 4 is the cartesian equation of the curve. (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (189,'199800103001','a) $$x+2y=5$$ ……(1);$$y^2+xy=6$$ …(2);Substitute $$x = 5-2y$$ from (1) int o (2);$$x=5-2y$$;$$y^2+(5-2y)y=6$$;$$\\Rightarrow y^2+5y+6=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (y-2)(y-3)=0$$;Therefore y = 2 or 3;When y = 2 (1) gives x = 5 - 2y = 1;When y = 3, (1) gives x = 5 - 2y = - 1;Therefore A and B are (1, - 2) and (-1, 3) (ANS);b) Therefore Distance AB;= $$\\sqrt{[1-(-1)]^2+[2-3]^2}$$;=$$\\sqrt{4+1}$$;=$$\\sqrt5$$;$$\\approx 2.236 units$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (190,'199800103002','$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=2x(x-3)=2x^2-6x$$;$$y=\\int 2x^2-6xdx$$;=$$2\\int x^2dx-6\\int xdx$$;=$$2(\\frac{1}{3}x^3)-6(\\frac{1}{2}x^2)+c$$;=$$\\frac{2}{3}x^3-3x^2+c$$ where c is the integration constant to be determined.;since (3, 6) is a point on the curve,	$$\\Rightarrow y=6$$ when $$x=3$$;$$\\Rightarrow 6=\\frac{2}{3}(3)^3-3(3)^2+c$$;$$\\Rightarrow 6=18-27+c$$;$$\\Rightarrow c=15$$;Hence ;$$y=\\frac{2}{3}x^3-3x^2+15$$ is the equation of the curve. (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (191,'199800103003','a) $$x(10-x)\\geq 24$$;$$\\Rightarrow 10x-x^2\\geq 24$$;$$\\Rightarrow x^2-10x+24\\leq 0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (x-4)(x-6)\\leq 0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 4\\leq x\\leq 6$$ (ANS);b) $$2y+x=k$$ ………(1);$$y^2+4x=20$$ …..(2);From (1), $$x = k - 2y$$,;Sub into (2),;$$y^2+4(k-2y)=20$$;$$\\Rightarrow y^2-8y+(4k-20)=0$$;since the line is tangent to the quadratic curve, equation (3) has only 1 real root. Therefore,;discriminant = 0;64 - 4(4k - 20) = 0;64 - 16k + 80 =0;16k = 144;k = 9 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (192,'199800103004','$$y=\\frac{6}{(1-2x)}$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=-\\frac{6}{(1-2x)^2}(-2)$$;=$$ \\frac{12}{(1-2x)^2}$$ (ANS);i) At x = 2;$$y=\\frac{6}{(1-2(2))}= \\frac{6}{(-3)}=-2$$;Thus the point is given by (2, - 2) and ;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{12}{(-3)^2}=\\frac{4}{3}$$;Gradient of the normal at point (2, - 2) is thus $$-\\frac{3}{4}$$;The equation of the normal is thus given by,;$$ \\frac{ (y-(-2))}{(x-2)}=-\\frac{3}{4}$$;$$\\Rightarrow 4(y+2)=-3(x-2)$$;$$\\Rightarrow 3x+4y+2=0$$ (ANS);ii) $$\\delta y\\approx \\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x} \\times  \\delta x$$;=$$\\frac{(4p)}{3}$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (193,'199800103005','a) $$(\\frac{x^2-3}{x})^5$$ has a general, $$T_r$$ term given as ;$$T_r=^5C_r(x)^r(\\frac{-3}{x})^{(5-r)}$$;where r = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.;Thus to find the term of $$x^1$$, we have;2r - (5 - r) = 1;3r = 6;r = 2;Thus the term of interest is the T2 term where,;$$T_2=^5C_2(x)^2(\\frac{-3}{x})^{(3)}$$;= (10)(-27)x;= -270x;therefore coefficient of x is - 270 (ANS);b)$$(1+p)^7=1+7p+^7C_2p^2+^7C_3p^3+...$$;=$$1+7p+21p^2+35p^3+...$$ (ANS);  By substituting $$p=x^2+2x^2$$;we have,;$$(1+x+2x^2)^7$$;=$$1+7(x+2x^2)+21(x+2x^2)^2+35(x+2x^2)^3+...$$;=$$1+(7x+14x^2)+21x^2(1+2x)^2+35x^3(1+2x)^3+...$$;The only two $$x^3$$ terms are in $$21x^2(1+2x)^2$$ and $$35x^3(1+2x)^3$$ which are given as,;$$21x^2(4x) and 35x^3$$ respectively. This can be combined as $$119x^3$$;Hence coefficient of $$x^3$$ in the expansion of $$(1+x+2x^2)^7$$ is 119. (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (194,'199800103006','img;i) Radius of the base of the water at height x is given by;$$r=(\\frac{20}{60})x=\\frac{1}{3}x$$;Volume, v, of t he water in the container is thus,;$$v=\\frac{1}{3}(\\pi r^2)x$$;=$$\\frac{1}{3}\\pi (\\frac{1}{3}x)^2x$$;=$$\\frac{1}{3}\\pi (\\frac{1}{9}x^2)x$$;=$$\\frac{ (\\pi x^3)}{27}$$ (Shown);ii)Now;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} v}{\\mathrm{d} t}=40cm^3s^{-1}$$ and ;$$ \\frac{ (\\pi x^2)}{9}=\\frac{ (\\pi (2)^2)}{9}=\\frac{ (4\\pi )}{9}$$ when x = 2;therefore ;$$40=(\\frac{ (4\\pi )}{9})(\\frac{\\mathrm{d} x}{\\mathrm{d} t})$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{\\mathrm{d} x}{\\mathrm{d} t}=40(\\frac{9}{(4\\pi )})= \\frac{90}{\\pi} $$;$$\\approx 28.6cms^{-1}$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (195,'199800103007','i) $$v=t^2-4t-5, t\\geq 0$$;$$\\Rightarrow  acceleration,a=\\frac{\\mathrm{d} v}{\\mathrm{d} t}=2t-4,t\\geq 0$$ (ANS); ii)   The distance of P from B is given by,;$$S=\\int vdt$$;=$$\\int (t^2-4t-5)dt$$;=$$\\frac{t^3}{3-2t^2-5t}+c$$;At t = 0, s =4;c = 4;Therefore distance of P from A is ;$$| \\frac{t^3}{3-2t^2-5t+4}|$$ (ANS);iii) When P comes to instantaneously to rest,;$$v=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow t^2-4t-5=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (t-5)(t+1)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow t=5$$;Therefore distance of P from A is;$$| \\frac{5^3}{3}-2(5)^2-5(5)+4|= 29 \\frac{1}{3}m$$ (ANS);iv)Between t = 0 to t = 5, distance travelled by P is $$\\frac{100}{3}m$$ ;as computed in part (iii). Between t = 5 to t = 10, the distance travelled by P is;$$\\int _5^10[t^2-4t-5]dt$$;=$$[\\frac{1}{3}t^3-2t^2-5t]_5^10$$;=$$[\\frac{1000}{3}-200-50]-[\\frac{1}{3}(5)^3-2(5)^2-(5)(5)]$$;=$$ \\frac{250}{3}-\\frac{-100}{3}$$;=$$ \\frac{350}{3}$$;Thus the total distance travelled by P from t = 0 to t = 10 is;$$ \\frac{350}{3} + \\frac{100}{3}$$ or 150m (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (196,'199800103008','a) From the diagram, by Pythagoras theorem, the adjacent side of the triangle with angle $$\\beta$$ is given by $$\\sqrt{1-p^2}$$;Thus $$\\tan \\beta=\\frac{p}{\\sqrt{1-p^2}}$$ where $$\\beta$$ is acute angle. (ANS);b) $$\\sin (90^{\\circ} -\\beta)=\\cos \\beta=\\frac{ (\\sqrt{1-p^2})}{1}=\\sqrt{1-p^2}$$ (ANS);from the diagram;c) $$\\sin (180^{\\circ} +\\beta)=[\\sin 180^{\\circ} -(-\\beta)]=\\sin -(\\beta)=-p$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (197,'199800103009','$$(1\\csc\\theta )(1-\\sin \\theta )$$=$$(1+\\frac{1}{\\sin \\theta })(1-\\sin \\theta )$$=$$ \\frac{ ((1+\\sin \\theta )(1-\\sin \\theta ))}{\\sin \\theta} $$=$$\\frac{ (1-\\sin ^2\\theta )}{\\sin \\theta} $$=$$\\frac{ (\\cos ^2\\theta )}{\\sin \\theta} $$=$$\\frac{\\cos \\theta }{\\sin \\theta} (\\cos \\theta )$$=$$\\cot \\theta \\cos \\theta $$ (Shown)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (198,'199800103010','a) $$AD = 8\\sin (0.92) = 6.36 cm...(1)$$;Similarly;$$OD = 8\\cos (0.92)=4.85 cm$$;$$DB = OB - OD = 8 - 4.85=3.15 cm.....(2)$$;$$AB = 8(0.92) = 7.36 cm.....(3)$$;Therefore perimeter of region ADB is AD + DB + AB or 16.9 cm (ANS);b) Area of sector OAB ;= $$\\frac{1}{2}r^2\\theta $$;=$$\\frac{1}{2}(8)^2(0.92)$$;=$$29.44cm^2$$;  Area of triangle OAC ;= $$\\frac{1}{2}(OA)(AC)$$;=$$\\frac{1}{2}(OA)(OA)\\tan 0.92)$$;=$$\\frac{1}{2}(OA)^2\\tan 0.92$$;=$$\\frac{1}{2}(8)^2\\tan 0.92$$;=$$42.02cm^2$$;therefore area of Q = 42.02 - 29.44 = $$12.6cm^2$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (199,'199800103011','a) Gradient of AX = - 2;therefore the equation of AX is ;$$ \\frac{ (y-2)}{(x-8)}=-2$$;$$\\Rightarrow y-2=-2x+16$$;$$y=-2x+18$$ (ANS);b) To find X, sole the simultaneous equations,;$$y=-2x+18$$ ……….(1);$$2y=x+10$$ ………..(2);Substitute $$y =  - 2x + 18$$ into (2) yield,;$$2(-2x+18)=x+10$$;$$\\Rightarrow -4x+36=x+10$$;$$\\Rightarrow 5x=26$$;$$x=5.2 and y=-2x+18=7.6$$;hence $$X -= (5.2, 7.6)$$ (ANS);c) since ;$$BC = 5BX$$;$$CX + BX = 5BX$$;$$CX = 4BX$$;$$i.e CX:BX = 4:1$$;Therefore;$$\\vec{OX}=\\frac{1}{5}(4\\vec{OB}+\\vec{OC})$$;$$\\vec{OC}=5\\vec{OX}-4\\vec{OB}$$;$$\\vec{OC}-=5(5.2,7.6)-4(2,6)-=(18,14)$$;Coordinates of C is (18, 14) (ANS);To find D, by the geometrical properties of parallelogram,;$$\\vec{AB}=\\vec{DC}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\vec{OB}-\\vec{OA}=\\vec{OC}-\\vec{OD}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\vec{OA}+\\vec{OC}=\\vec{OB}+\\vec{OD}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\vec{OD}=\\vec{OA}+\\vec{OC}-\\vec{OB}$$;$$\\vec{OD}-=(8,2)+(18,14)-(2,6)-=(24,10)$$;coordinates of D is (24, 10) (ANS);d) Length BC;= $$\\sqrt{(18-2)^2+(14-6)^2}$$;=$$\\sqrt{16^2+8^2}$$;=$$8\\sqrt{2^2+1^2}$$;=$$8(\\sqrt5)$$;=$$8\\sqrt5$$ units;Length AX ;= $$\\sqrt{(8-5.2)^2+(2-7.6)^2}$$;=$$\\sqrt{(2.8)^2+(5.6)^2}$$;=$$(2.8)\\sqrt{1^2+2^2}$$;=$$2.8\\sqrt5$$ units; Therefore;Area of parallelogram ABCD is given by;Area = (AX)BC};=$$(2.8\\sqrt5)(8\\sqrt5)$$;=(22.4)(5);=$$112 units^2$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (200,'199800103012','a) i) $$2\\sin 2x+1=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\sin 2x=-\\frac{1}{2}$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2x=210^{\\circ} ,330^{\\circ} ,570^{\\circ} ,690^{\\circ} $$;$$\\Rightarrow x=105^{\\circ} , 165^{\\circ} , 285^{\\circ} , 345^{\\circ} $$ (ANS);ii) $$secy(1+\\tan y)=6\\cos ecy$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\tan ^2y+\\tan y-6=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (\\tan y+3)(\\tan y-2)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\tan y=-3 or \\tan y=2$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=108.43^{\\circ} ,288.43^{\\circ}  or y=63.43^{\\circ} ,243.43^{\\circ} $$;$$y=64.43^{\\circ} , 108.43^{\\circ} , 243.43^{\\circ} , 288.43^{\\circ} $$ (ANS);b) $$\\cos (\\frac{ (\\pi t)}{5})=0.6$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{ (\\pi t)}{5}=\\cos ^{-1}(0.6)$$;=0.9273,5.3559;t = 1.48, 8.52 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (201,'199800103013','i) Required area;= $$\\int _1^2(7-3x)dx-\\int _1^2(\\frac{4}{x^2})dx$$;=$$\\int _1^2(7-3x-\\frac{4}{x^2})dx$$;=$$[7x-\\frac{3}{2}x^2+\\frac{4}{x}]_1^2$$;=$$(14 - 6 + 2) - (7 - \\frac{3}{2} + 4)$$;=10 - 9.5;=$$0.5 units^2$$ (ANS);ii) Required Volume;= $$\\pi \\int _1^2(7-3x)^2dx-\\pi \\int _1^2(\\frac{4}{x^2})^2dx$$;=$$\\pi [\\int _1^2(7-3x)^2dx-\\int _1^2(\\frac{16}{x^4})dx]$$;=$$\\pi {[-\\frac{1}{9}(7-3x)^3]_1^2-[-16}{(3x^3)]_1^2}$$;=$$\\pi {\\frac{1}{9}(64-1)-( \\frac{16}{3}-\\frac{2}{3})}$$;=$$\\pi {7-\\frac{14}{3}}$$;=$$\\frac{ (7\\pi )}{3}$$;$$\\approx 7.33 units^3$$  ');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (202,'199800103014','a) $$y=27+12x+3x^2-2x^3$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=12+6x-6x^2=6(2+x-x^2)$$;$$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d} ^{2}y}{\\mathrm{d} x^{2}}=6(1-2x)$$;To find stationary points, solve;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2+x-x^2=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (2-x)(1+x)=0$$;$$x=2 or x=-1$$;When x = -1, y = 27 - 12 + 3 + 2 = 20;when x = 2, y = 27 + 24 +12 - 6 = 47;Now when x = - 1,;$$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d} ^{2}y}{\\mathrm{d} x^{2}}=18>0$$;Therefore (-1, 20) is a minimum point on the curve. (ANS);When x = 2,;$$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d} ^{2}y}{\\mathrm{d} x^{2}}=-18<0$$;Therefore (2, 47) is a maximum point on the curve. (ANS);b) i) Let h be the height of the tan k, then area of the rectangular tan k;=$$2(2xh+2x^2+hx)$$;=$$2(3hx+2x^2)$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2(3hx+2x^2)=48$$;$$\\Rightarrow 3hx+2x^2=24$$;$$\\Rightarrow 3hx=24-2x^2$$;$$\\Rightarrow h=\\frac{8}{x}-\\frac{ (2x)}{3}$$ (ANS);ii) Let v be the volume of the \\tan k, then volume = length x width x height;$$v=(2x)(x)(h)=2x^2(\\frac{8}{x}-\\frac{ (2x)}{3})$$;$$\\Rightarrow v=16x-\\frac{ (4x^3)}{3}$$ (ANS);Now;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} v}{\\mathrm{d} t}=16-4x^2$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} v}{\\mathrm{d} t}=0\\Rightarrow 4x^2=16$$;$$\\Rightarrow x^2=4$$;$$x\\pm 2$$;x must be positive;When x = 2, ;$$h=\\frac{8}{2}-\\frac{4}{3}=\\frac{8}{3 }and v=\\frac{64}{3}cm^3$$;Therefore dimensions of the \\tan k for which the volume is a maximum are given by length of 4 cm, width of 2 cm and height of $$\\frac{8}{3}$$cm (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (203,'199800103015','img;a) From $$\\vec{LP}=\\frac{2}{5}\\vec{LM}$$;we have thus;LP:LM = 2:3;$$\\vec{OP}=\\frac{1}{5}(3\\vec{OL}+2\\vec{OM})$$;$$\\vec{OP}=\\frac{1}{5}(3d+2e)$$;Hence, ;$$\\vec{OQ}=\\lambda \\vec{OP}=\\frac{\\lambda }{5} (3d+2e)$$ (ANS);b) From $$\\vec{LQ}=mu \\vec{LN}$$;we may write ;$$LQ:LN =\\mu :(1-\\mu)$$;$$\\vec{OQ}=(1-\\mu)\\vec{OL}+\\mu\\vec{ON}$$;=$$(1-\\mu)d+\\mu(2d+2e)$$;=$$(1+\\mu)d+2\\mu e$$ (ANS);To find $$\\lambda and \\mu$$, ;by equating $$\\vec{OQ}$$ from i) and ii), yield;$$ \\frac{(3\\lambda)}{5}d+\\frac{(2\\lambda)}{5}e=(1+\\mu)d+2\\mu e$$;$$\\Rightarrow 1+\\mu=\\frac{ (3\\lambda)}{5}$$ ……..(1);$$\\mu=\\frac{\\lambda}{5}$$ ………….(2);Eliminating $$\\lambda$$ from (1) and (2), we have;$$1+\\mu=3\\mu$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2\\mu=1$$;$$\\mu=\\frac{1}{2}$$;Substitute into (2), we have,;$$\\lambda=5\\mu=\\frac{5}{2}$$;Therefore $$\\mu=0.5 and \\lambda=2.5$$ (ANS)');
