INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (205,'199800104001','a) Let;$$f(x)=x^2+(k-1)x+k^2-16$$;$$\\Rightarrow f(3)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 9+3(k-1)+k^2-16=0$$;$$k^2+3k-10=0$$;$$(k-2)(k+5)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow k=2 or k=-5$$;when k = 2, f(-4) = 16+(- 4) + 4 - 16=0;Therefore k = 2 has to be discarded since f(- 4) = 0;When k = - 5,;f(- 4) = 16 - 6(- 4) + 25 - 16 = $$49 \\neq  0$$;Hence value of k is - 5 (ANS);b)Let $$f(x)=8x^3-2x^2-5x-1$$;  Note that f(1) = 8 - 2 - 5 - 1 = 0,;therefore (x - 1) is a factor of f(x).;By long division;img;Therefore ;$$f(x)=8x^3-2x^2-5x-1$$;=$$(x-1)(8x^2+6x+1)$$;$$f(x)=0\\Rightarrow (x-1)(8x^2+6x+1)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (x-1)(2x+1)(4x+1)=0$$;$$x=-\\frac{1}{2} or -\\frac{1}{4} or 1$$ (ANS);To solve $$8\\tan ^2\\theta -2\\tan \\theta -5=\\cot \\theta $$,;we have,;$$8\\tan ^2\\theta -2\\tan \\theta -5=\\frac{1}{\\tan \\theta }$$;$$\\Rightarrow 8\\tan ^3\\theta -2\\tan ^2\\theta -5\\tan \\theta -1=0$$;Thus by replacing $$\\tan \\theta $$ by x, we have ;$$8x^2-2x^2-5x-1=0$$;from which are already obtained ;$$x=1,-\\frac{1}{2} or -\\frac{1}{4}$$;Therefore ;$$x=\\tan \\theta =1,-\\frac{1}{2} or -\\frac{1}{4}$$ are the values of $$\\tan \\theta $$;Now;$$\\tan \\theta =1\\Rightarrow \\theta =45^{\\circ} $$;$$\\tan \\theta =-\\frac{1}{2}\\Rightarrow \\theta =180^{\\circ} -26.6^{\\circ} =153.4^{\\circ} $$;$$\\tan \\theta =-\\frac{1}{4}\\Rightarrow \\theta =180^{\\circ} -14^{\\circ} =166^{\\circ} $$;Therefore values of ;$$\\theta =45^{\\circ} ,153.4^{\\circ} ,166^{\\circ} $$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (206,'199800104002','a) i) Let a and d be the first term and common difference of the A.P.;Now;       $$T_5$$ = 5th term = a + 4d;       $$T_2$$ = 2nd term = a + d;Given;$$T_5=3T_2$$;$$\\Rightarrow a+4d=3(a+d)$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2a=d$$;$$d=2a$$;To show that $$S_8 = 4S_4$$, we have,;$$S_4=\\frac{4}{2}(2a+3d)$$;=$$2(2a+6a)$$;=$$16a$$;$$S_8=\\frac{8}{2}(2a+7d)=4(2a+14a)=64a$$;Now$$\\frac{S_8}{S_4}=\\frac{ (64a)}{(16a)}=4$$;Hence S8 = 4S4(shown);ii) $$S_8=sum_{(r=1)}^8T_r and S_4=sum_{(r=1)}^4T_r$$;Hence,;$$S_8-S_4=240$$;$$\\Rightarrow 4S_4-S_4=240$$;$$\\Rightarrow 3S_4=240$$;$$\\Rightarrow S_4=16a=80$$;$$a=\\frac{80}{16}=5$$ (ANS);b) Now;$$a+96r=0$$ …….(1);$$\\frac{a}{(1-r)}=32$$ …..(2);From (2) a = 32(1 - r), substitute into (1), yield,;$$32(1-r)+96r=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 32=-64r$$;$$\\Rightarrow r=-\\frac{32}{64}=-0.5$$;Substutute into (2), we have;a = 32(1 - r) =32(1.5) = 48;Hence ;$$T_8=ar^7=48(-\\frac{1}{2})^7=-\\frac{3}{8}$$ (ANS);c)  Let a and r be the first term and common difference of the G.P respectively.;Thus;$$a=10$$;$$r=\\frac{11}{10}=1.1$$;To find the least number of terms n such that Sn > 8000, we have,;$$S_r=\\frac{ (a(1-r)^n)}{(1-r)}= \\frac{ (a(r^n-1))}{(r-1)}>8000$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{ (10[(1.1)^n-1])}{(1.1-1)}>8000$$;$$\\Rightarrow 100[(1.1)^n-1]>8000$$;$$\\Rightarrow 1.1^n>81$$;$$\\Rightarrow n\\log (1.1)>\\log 81$$;$$\\Rightarrow n>\\frac{ (\\log 81)}{(\\log 1.1)}$$$$\\Rightarrow n>\\frac{1.908485}{0.041393}$$;$$\\Rightarrow n>46.11$$;Therefore n = 47 is the least number of terms such that Sn > 8000 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (207,'199800104003','img;img;a) i) $$y+10=Ak^x$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\lg (y+10)=\\lg A+x(\\lg k)$$;Therefore A graph of \\lg (y + 10) against x is a straight line with gradient of lg  k and lg (y + 10) - intercept of lg A.;Gradient of graph = $$\\frac{1.625}{8}=0.203125$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\lg k=0.203125$$;$$k=10^0.203125=1.9953$$;$$k\\approx 2.00$$ (ANS);$$\\lg A=0.3$$;$$A=1.99526$$;$$A\\approx 2$$ (ANS);ii) when ;$$y=0\\Rightarrow \\lg (y+10)=\\lg 10=1$$;From the graph, x = 3.45 (ANS);b) i) Given;$$px^3+qy^2=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{2}p+\\frac{1}{4}q=1 or 2p+q=4$$…..(1);$$- \\frac{p}{q}=\\frac{3}{4} or 4p+3q=0$$ …………(2);substitute q = 4 - 2p from (1) into (2), yield,;$$4p+3(4-2p)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2p=12$$;$$p=6$$ (ANS);From (1), q = 4 - 2p = 4 - 2(6) = - 8 (ANS);ii) Now ; $$6x^3-8y^2=1$$;when;$$x^3=k,y^2=4$$;we have ;$$6k-8(4)=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow 6k=33$$;$$k=5.5$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (208,'199800104004','a) $$\\cos 2\\theta =\\cos \\theta $$;$$\\Rightarrow 2\\cos ^2\\theta -1=\\cos \\theta $$;$$\\Rightarrow 2\\cos ^2\\theta -\\cos \\theta -1=0$$;$$\\cos \\theta =\\frac{ (2\\pm \\sqrt{4+8})}{4}=\\frac{ (1\\pm \\sqrt3)}{2}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\cos \\theta =1.3660(rejected) or -0.3660$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\theta =\\cos ^{-1}(-0.3660)$$;=$$115.5^{\\circ}  or 248.5^{\\circ} $$ (ANS);b) Let;$$4\\sin x-2\\cos x=R\\sin (x-\\alpha )$$;$$\\Rightarrow 4\\sin x-2\\cos x=R\\sin x\\cos \\alpha -R\\cos x\\sin \\alpha $$;$$R\\cos \\alpha =4$$ …..(1);$$R\\sin \\alpha =2$$…….(2);To find R, consider $$(1)^2+(2)^2$$;$$\\Rightarrow R^2(\\cos ^2\\alpha +\\sin ^2\\alpha )=R^2=4^2+2^2=20$$;$$\\Rightarrow R=2\\sqrt5$$;To find a, consider (2) }{ (1), we have;$$\\tan \\alpha =\\frac{1}{2} \\Rightarrow  \\alpha =\\tan ^{-1}(\\frac{1}{2})=26.57^{\\circ} =0.4636rad$$;Thus $$4\\sin  x - 2 \\cos  x$$ ;= $$2\\sqrt5\\sin (x-0.4636)$$ (ANS);  To find the x coordinates of the points of intersection of the curves y = 4sin  x and y = 2cos  x + 1, we solve the equation,;$$4\\sin x=2\\cos x+1$$;$$\\Rightarrow 4\\sin x-2\\cos x=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2\\sqrt5\\sin (x-0.4636)=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\sin (x-0.4636)= \\frac{1}{(2\\sqrt5)}=0.2236$$;$$\\Rightarrow x-0.4636=0.2255,2.9164$$;$$x=0.6891 or 3.3800$$;Hence x = 0.69 rad or x = 3.38 rad. (ANS);c)Therefore tan Atan B = 8 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (209,'199800104005','a) $$2^{(x+1)}+2^x=9$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2(2^x)+2^x=9$$;$$\\Rightarrow 3(2^x)=9$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2^x=3$$;$$\\Rightarrow x\\lg 2=\\lg 3$$;$$\\Rightarrow x=\\frac{ (\\lg 3)}{(\\lg 2)}$$;=$$ \\frac{0.4771}{0.3010}$$;$$\\approx 1.5850 = 1.59$$ (ANS);b)$$3^x=27(3^y)=3^3(3^y)=3^{(3+y)}$$;$$x=3+y$$ ………..…(1);$$\\lg (x+2y)=\\lg 5+\\lg 3=(\\lg 5 \\times  3)=\\lg 15$$;$$\\Rightarrow x+2y=15$$ ...….(2);  Substitute x = 3 + y from (1) \\int o (2), yield,;$$(3+y)+2y=15$$;$$\\Rightarrow 3y=12$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=4$$ (ANS);And hence x = 3 + y = 3 + 4 = 7 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (210,'199800104006','i) $$v=20e^{-\\frac{t}{4}}$$;When t = 0, v = 20;$$t\\rightarrow oo, v=0  since  e^{-\\frac{t}{4}}\\rightarrow 0  when  t \\rightarrow  \\infty $$;ii) When v = 10, we have;$$10=20e^{-\\frac{t}{4}}$$;$$\\Rightarrow e^{\\frac{t}{4}}=\\frac{20}{10}=2$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{t}{4}=\\ln 2=0.6931$$;$$t=4(0.6931)=2.7726$$;$$t\\approx 2.77$$ (ANS);iii) Acceleration of the particle is given by,;$$a=\\frac{\\mathrm{d} v}{\\mathrm{d} t}=(20e^{-\\frac{t}{4}}(-\\frac{1}{4})=-5e^{-\\frac{t}{4}}$$;When v = 10, we have t = 2.7726, and hence,;$$a=\\frac{\\mathrm{d} v}{\\mathrm{d} t}=-5e^{\\frac{-2.7726}{4}}=-5(0.5)$$;$$a=-2.5$$ (ANS);iv) Displacement, S, is given by;$$S=\\int _0^tvdt$$;=$$20\\int _0^te^{\\frac{-t}{4}}dt$$;=$$20[-4e^{\\frac{-t}{4}}]_0^t$$;=$$80(1-e^{\\frac{-t}{4}})$$ (ANS);Where S is the displacement from O such that S = 0 when t = 0.');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (211,'199800104007','a) i) $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} }{\\mathrm{d} x}(3-2x)^10$$;=$$10(3-2x)^9(-2)$$;=$$-20(3-2x)^9$$ (ANS);ii) Now;$$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d} }{\\mathrm{d} times} ^2\\ln x$$;=$$2x\\ln x+x^2(\\frac{1}{x})$$;=$$x+2x\\ln x$$ (ANS);  b) $$y^2=x^2y+6x$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2y\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=x^2\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}+2xy+16$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{ (2xy+16)}{(2y-x^2)}$$;Now (2, 6) is a point on the curve and its tangent at this point has gradient of;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{ (2(2)(6)+16)}{(2(6)-(2)^2)}= \\frac{40}{8}=5$$;Thus the tangent this to the curve at this point is given by;$$(y-6)=5(x-2)$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=5x-4$$ (ANS);c)i) $$y=\\frac{ (\\cos x)}{(\\sin x-4)}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{ ((\\sin x-4)(-\\sin x)-(\\cos x)(\\cos x))}{(\\sin x-4)^2}$$   ;=$$ \\frac{ (4\\sin x-1)}{(\\sin x-4)^2}$$ (ANS);ii) To find x for which y is stationary, we solve for x such that,;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 4\\sin x-1=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\sin x=\\frac{1}{4}=0.25$$;$$\\Rightarrow x=0.2527,2.8889$$;x = 0.253 or 2.89 (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (212,'199800104008','a) $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=3x^2+\\frac{2}{x}$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=\\int (3x^2+\\frac{2}{x})dx$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=\\int 3x^2dx+\\int \\frac{2}{x}dx$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=x^3+2\\ln x+c$$ where c is the integration constant. ;Now (1, 3) is a point on the curve, therefore,;3 = 1 + 0 + c or c = 2;Hence;$$y=x^3+2\\ln x+2$$ (ANS);b)  $$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} }{\\mathrm{d} x}=(2x+\\sin 2x)$$;=$$2+2\\cos 2x$$;=$$2+2(2\\cos ^2x-1)$$;=$$4\\cos ^2x$$;Therefore;$$\\int _{\\frac{\\pi }{2}}^\\pi \\cos ^2xdx$$;=$$[\\frac{1}{4}(2x+\\sin 2x)]_{( \\frac{\\pi }{2})}^\\pi $$;=$$\\frac{1}{4}[2\\pi -\\pi ]$$;=$$ \\frac{\\pi }{4}$$ (ANS);c)i)Area = $$\\int _0^2ydx$$;=$$\\int _0^2(\\frac{1}{(\\sqrt{4x+1})})dx$$;=$$ [\\frac{2}{4}(\\sqrt{4x+1})]_0^2$$;=$$\\frac{1}{2}[\\sqrt9-\\sqrt1]$$;=$$1 units^2$$ (ANS);ii)$$v=\\pi \\int _0^2y^2dx$$;=$$\\pi \\int _0^2(\\frac{1}{(4x+1)})dx$$;=$$\\frac{\\pi }{4}[\\ln (4x+1)]_0^2$$;=$$\\frac{\\pi }{4}\\ln 9$$;= $$1.73 units^3$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (213,'199800104009','i) $$x=t^2-t\\Rightarrow \\frac{\\mathrm{d} x}{\\mathrm{d} t}=2t-1$$;$$y=2t+1\\Rightarrow \\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} t}=2$$;$$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} x}=\\frac{\\frac{\\mathrm{d} y}{\\mathrm{d} t}}{\\frac{\\mathrm{d} x}{\\mathrm{d} t}}=\\frac{2}{(2t-1)}$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{2}{(2t-1)}= \\frac{2}{5}$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2t-1=5$$;t=3 (ANS);ii) The coordinates at point p is given by substituting t = 3 into y,;Therefore $$P -= (6, 7)$$;Gradient of normal at P;= $$-\\frac{5}{2}$$;Therefore equation of normal at P is;$$ \\frac{ (y-7)}{(x-6)}=-\\frac{5}{2}$$;$$2(y-7)+5(x-6)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2y+5x-44=0$$;2y+5x=44(Shown);iii) To find t when normal at P intersects the curve again, substitute ;$$x^2=t^2-1 and y=2t+1$$ into 2y + 5x = 44.;$$\\Rightarrow 2(2t+1)+5(t^2-t)=44$$;$$\\Rightarrow 5t^2-t-42=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow (5t+14)(t-3)=0$$;$$\\Rightarrow t=-\\frac{14}{5} or t=3(N.A)$$;Therefore $$t=-\\frac{14}{5}$$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (214,'199800104010','a) $$x=3\\sin \\alpha +\\cos \\alpha $$ ……(1);$$y=\\sin \\alpha -2\\cos \\alpha $$ …….(2);By eliminating $$\\sin \\alpha $$ from (1) and (2),;$$x-3y=3\\sin \\alpha +\\cos \\alpha -3(\\sin \\alpha -2\\cos \\alpha )$$;=$$7\\cos \\alpha $$;Similarly, by eliminating \\cos a from (1) and (2),;$$2x+y=2(3\\sin \\alpha +\\cos \\alpha )-(\\sin \\alpha -2\\cos \\alpha )$$;=$$7\\sin \\alpha $$;Therefore;$$\\sin \\alpha =\\frac{1}{7}(2x+y)$$ (ANS);$$\\cos \\alpha =\\frac{1}{7}(x-3y)$$ (ANS);To find the cartesian equation, by eliminating a from the equation, we have,;$$\\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{49}(2x+y)^2+\\frac{1}{49}(x-3y)^2=1$$;$$\\Rightarrow (2x+y)^2+(x-3y)^2=49$$;$$\\Rightarrow (4x^2+4xy+y^2)+(x^2-6xy+9y^2)=49$$;$$\\Rightarrow 5x^2-2xy+10y^2=49$$ (ANS);b)$$(y-3)^2=1+x^2$$;$$\\Rightarrow (y-3)^2=1+\\cot ^2\\theta $$;$$\\Rightarrow (y-3)^2\\csc^2\\theta $$;$$\\Rightarrow y-3=\\pm\\csc\\theta $$;$$\\Rightarrow y=3\\pm\\csc\\theta $$;Given also y = 1 when $$\\theta =\\frac{\\pi }{6}$$;$$\\theta =\\frac{\\pi }{6}\\Rightarrow\\csc\\theta \\csc\\frac{\\pi }{6}=2$$;$$\\Rightarrow y=3\\csc\\theta =5(N.A)$$;And$$y=3\\csc\\theta =1$$;Hence the expression for y is given by $$y=3\\csc\\theta $$ (ANS)');
INSERT INTO `DBManagement_answer` (`id`,`question_id_id`,`content`) VALUES (215,'199900101001','$$2x+2y=1$$ ……….(1);$$4x^2+y^2=5$$ …..(2);From (1);$$y=1-2x$$………….(3);Substitute (3) \\int o (2),;$$4x^2+(1-2x)^2=5$$;$$4x^2+1-4x+4x^2=5$$;$$8x^2-4x-4=0$$;$$2x^2-x-1=0$$;$$(2x+1)(x-1)=0$$;$$x=\\frac{1}{2} or x=1$$;Substitute $$x=-\\frac{1}{2}, 1$$ \\int o (3);$$y=1-2(-\\frac{1}{2})=2 or y=1-2(1)=-1$$;$$x=-\\frac{1}{2},y=2 or x=1,y=-1$$ (ANS)');
